Scout is a printable tribot designed for teaching the Boy Scout robotics merit badge. http://www.scouting.org/scoutsource/BoyScouts/AdvancementandAwards/MeritBadges/mb-ROBO.aspx I've marked this as a derivative of MiniSkyBot because I was inspired by it and because Scout still uses the wheels from that project. The frame itself is a complete redesign with similar but different goals. Goals:
Provide a kit that meets the merit badge requirements with parts totaling < $50 USD. -Minimum printed parts
-Minimum vitamins
-Accommodate an arduino diecimila or nano.
-use a 9V battery.
-Flexible enough to allow boys to improve and extend the design. The frame is a single printed piece. The tabs for holding the servo motors can be tapped with a 4mm tap to avoid the need for nuts. The top holes can be tapped with a 3mm tap to screw on an arduino without nuts. The bracket will hold a 9v battery with just friction. The rear battery bracket has a friction fit cup for a ball bearing caster. Large holes in the bracket minimize the amount of plastic needed and allow wires to be routed up to the arduino. Cost
Since affordability was a major consideration, here's a run down of the final project cost. The plastic cost is just the cost of a roll divided by the number of kits we built. There was lots of plastic left over and the boys are using it to design improvements. Frame & Wheels $7.86 (plastic from Makerbot)
Tires (2) $2.36 (Hardware store o-rings)
4mm bolts (4) $0.84
wheels screws (4) $0.96
Servos futaba (2) $8.38 (purchased new in bulk on ebay)
Arduino Nano $18.99 (purchased new on ebay)
Ultrasonic $3.90 (purchased new on ebay)
9v connector $0.81 (Radio Shack)
DC power plug $1.86 (Radio Shack)
9V battery $1.25
Total: $47.21

Print the frame bracket. Tap the bracket holes. Print two wheels. Mount the servo horns to the wheels. Put on o-rings or rubber bands for traction. Assemble. Route wires up to the arduino.

description.text:
3d printing filament is highly hydrophilic and therefore it is important to store the filament after opening in a very low humidity environment. 
It is best to keep the humidity below 20%. Here in the Netherlands, the humidity is around 45-50% in house and therefore I decided to store all my filament in airtight containers together with silica gel
The filament used for printing is also stored in the airtight box and is fed to the printer using a bowden tube
I designed bowden connectors for the tube and a filament rol holder to be used inside the container. In this way you can leave the filament connected to the extruder and still keep the rol of filament inside the airtight 'low humidity' container.

Printer:

Achatz easydelta remodeled

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm with 0.4mm nozzle

Infill:

50%

Building the box There are STL files for using a 9.5mm bowden tube fittings, or for using connectors with a 4 or 6 mm hole to simply insert the bowden tube directly into the connector. The filament holder is created using
  • 8mm rod/threaded rod (i used 133mm length )
  • 2 ball bearings 22x8x7mm
  • either a 22mm steel/aluminium tube, or a 19mm electrical pvc tube. (i used 96mm length)
  • printed parts that holds the ball bearing and fits over the tube on both sides
    • There is a separate STL file for the 22mm tube parts Predrill the holes in the box and screw the parts to the box using small woodscrews. Silica Gel Do not just throw in a couple of silica gel bags as they do soak up the moisture, but in return when saturated these bags will make the air more humid again. Therefore the silica gel must be replaced in time. It is best to use silica gel with indicators. The color of the silica gel will change when they are saturated and need to be replaced. I dry my silica gel in a oven at 130C for a couple of hours and it is amazing to see how much water is contained. Be careful when using a oven, ensure the temperature is not above the 120-130C and ensure the silica gel is able to handle this This is the moisture indicating silica gel I use: http://www.xtrack.nl/product/silica-gel-orange-gel-500-gram-blik/ the website also contains instructions on drying the silica gel in a oven Airtight box I bought a couple of 44L sealed box which stores about 8 filament boxes/10 rolls each, i bought mine from http://www.goedkopeopbergbox.nl/opbergbox-luchtdicht-44-ltr but these boxes are common for sale in many other countries and places. Just google for 44L or 44 liter airtight box / sealed box / weathertight box / ...

description.text:
This was created in reaction to the New Museum challenge and the simple question - what could we make that would make life easier. My partner replied "something to make sure your bathroom stall doesnt pop open and is also a hook for hanging a purse or jacket." The great features of the design are:
  • it folds up for portability
  • the weight of the purse or jacket is what keeps it in place and provides the locking power
  • it can be printed in one build
  • you can add words to the side if you want to mark it occupied in a personal way
    • This was not a derivative, but instead an original design. It is an attempt to solve a common problem with steel doors and their insufficient locks in public bathrooms. The very low expense means that it is affordable for all, and it can be scaled for your most common everyday situations if needed. (for instance if your office restroom has extra thick doors) The design includes a beveled slot so that it should adjust to most door sizes.

Instructions for printing on your Makerbot:
Print in your desired color with one build. place the vertical part in the top part and then slide the pin thru both. A dab of plastic glue to fix the pin onto one or the other parts might be advisable. The pin is printed laying down for strength against shearing. Instructions for use:
When you are in the restroom, take the lock&hook out of your purse or pocket and flip out the vertical piece as seen in the renderings. slide the vertical piece in between the door and door frame until the top rests on the door top. hang your jacket or purse for extra latching power.

comments.text: Well I'm glad it worked for you, was it freshwater? I based my 99% on some math about the standard GoPro lens and the optics of water. The maximum Horizontal FOV of a GoPro(3,4&5) is 122.6° . When you shoot with 6 of them that gives you about 16° of overlap per stitch. However, in salt water your FOV will be reduced by about 33% which means an H.FOV of only 81° you'd need to add a fifth camera to get 360° of coverage. Completely fresh water would give you a magnification of about 25% which I suppose would give you very narrow coverage, on the horizontal. I didn't math it out, but I don't think it would cover you on the vertical. I didn't do all the math myself until just now, but I know the manufacturer for a very similar rig warns that it doesn't work underwater https://freedom360.us/shop/f360-explorer/ . And rigs that are designed to work underwater come have giant curved housings that compensate for the FOV bend. https://www.bhphotovideo.com/bnh/controller/home?A=details&O=&Q=&ap=y&c3api=1876%2C%7Bcreative%7D%2C%7Bkeyword%7D&gclid=Cj0KCQjw8b_MBRDcARIsAKJE7lmiQsZSiTnl0Axis34L4w4RGmyn-NoXp2OQNR1-TW1MazJcAnejOnsaAtYoEALw_wcB&is=REG&sku=1217924

Has anyone of you ever experienced the filament to move away from the gear wheel and loose a print for such a stupid thing?
I found out that especially with slippery and flexible filaments like nylon this can happen as no matter how much you tighten the screws of the extruder idler the filament just departs the gear wheel to one side or the other and the printer stops extruding. I redesigned the whole extruder idler from zero as I only had an STL file of it.
The new one is made in two parts so you can fit the bearing and after that fit the extended guiding part. I hope you like it, so far I have not experienced anymore the filament to depart to either side or any other problem with it. Please feel free to give me any hints and suggestions. ENJOY! title: Raspberry Pi B+ / Pi 2 clam shell case

description.text:
Another Raspberry Pi B+ / Pi 2 case. The differences to all those great cases out there on Thingiverse are:
  • Self centering clam-shell design: Light will not shine though the gaps, robust enclosure
  • No lateral space limitation for heat sinks
  • Additional round 5mm hole for some GPIO cables
  • Combines features of other cases:
    • The holes are well fit within an intentional tolerance of 0.5mm
    • Well tightened by common 10mm M3 screws and nuts
    • By using longer screws case can be stacked - see i.e. "usb_hub_shell" for DA-70215
    • Two holes for 2mm light gathering acrylic rods
    • Should be well printable without supports
    • Added a version with two M3 mounting holes and 70mm separation
    • If you like to add your own holes, mounting options or like to close the venting grid, I have provided the corresponding STEP files. At this point a friendly reminder for Pi Owners: There are different USB cables out there. Watch out for the AWG number which is related to the diameter of the copper wire. Cheap (4€) and shi**y ones are around 34AWG (ca. 0.44V voltage drop @ 500mA and 1m) and best (8€) are around 20AWG (ca. 0.02V voltage drop @ 500mA and 1m). This means that your cheapest cable provides less than 4,6V to you Pi which will hardly operate and be in the low-voltage mode.
Remove all spurious filament, blobs and uneven surfaces from the clam-shell fitting AND the 8 inner rods to ensure a minimal gap and good fitting.

title: Luna Park Electric Tower- Coney Island Play Set

description.text:
Inspired by the Gothic Cathedral Playset here on Thingiverse, this is the first of several fantasy architecture models based on historic Coney Island buildings that I plan on creating. The original Luna Park was created in 1903 by Frederic Thompson. The original postmodern architect, Thompson was a rebel who was kicked out the Beaux Arts Academy in Paris. He created Luna Park- a fantasy landscape in Coney Island, comprised of scores of minarets and towers, combining architectural styles ranging from far eastern to renaissance. At night, all of Luna Park was magically transformed into an electric fantasy as it was illuminated by over 100,000 light bulbs. Believe it or not, this particular tower was a big influence on the Metropolitan Life Insurance Tower in Manhattan. (Coincidentally, Frederic Thompson was born on October 31, 1873- 138 years before this file was uploaded- Happy Birthday Fred!) Please note that this is my first Thingiverse creation, and I do not have currently have access to a 3D printer to test this model, so any feedback from anyone in the community is appreciated! This is definitely a work in progress. Print one and send me a photo! Any Brooklynites interested in doing a print for me, please hit me up in the comments. I would be happy to barter! Update: 7/1/2012
I've updated this thing with successfully printed files created by Jason Batukis and the MakerBot Botfarm for the 2012 Mermaid Parade trophies. Thanks Guys!

Once all three sections are printed, glue them together. The model is meant to be printed in white ABS, but its your call! A clear or semi transparent material would be really cool to try- clear PLA?.

description.text:
This is my first attempt at making a printable object. It is a version of the "sanitary toothpick dispensers" that you might see at restaurants. There's an old one floating around my house so I decided to copy it to get some practice with openscad. Since this is my first time, and I don't yet own a 3DP, I'm not sure this is actually printable. I'd appreciate any feedback on things I can correct to make either the design or the file itself more easily printed. Some of the concerns I have about it:
  • The walls are 90mm high and only 1mm thick. I'm not sure what the guidelines are for structural stability.
  • The sloped ramp inside the dispenser is not supported, so I'm not sure if it will print properly.
  • I'm not sure how well the pieces will fit together after printing.

  • Ideally, there should be stops so that the cylinder will only rotate about 100 degrees. It should work fine without them, but it will be possible to dump toothpicks into the bottom, unused section.

  • Also, I'm not at all certain that it will work as designed. So there's that.
    • If you have any suggestions please let me know. Thanks to mikeq for pointing out my error with the difference function.

If you decide to print this, please either look over the OpenScad code first to make sure you're reasonably confident it has a chance at working, or let me know what you'd like changed and I will do so.
Assembly should be simple. Insert the cylinder into the cabinet, and insert the knobs through the matching holes from the outside. If there is not enough friction to hold the knobs in place, I was planning to use a drop or two of glue.
To operate, just rotate the cylinder so that the slot is inside, then out again to receive a toothpick.

Thanks for checking out my thing.  This thing is a frosting extruder much like the kind you would see a baker using to frost their goodies. I thought of making this for the New Museum Design Challenge after looking at the things I enjoy doing and thinking of ways I could improve it with the power of 3D Printing.
Usually when I go to add icing to muffins or frosting to a cake I take a common zip lock bag and put my icing or frosting into it and cut the corner off. sometimes this works and sometimes it's pretty messy. I know frosting bags and tips are fairly easy to come by at kitchen stores but I felt that a truly customizable tool would be what I would want to use to really give my treats a personalized touch.
With that in mind I set out to design an easy to use kit that used almost no extra parts beyond what the Thing-O-Matic 3D printer could produce.  Alongside the basic kit of parts I've created a wide array of nozzles to be used, Round tips, square, rectangle, slotted, and star tips. I know there are a massive number of tip designs and I hope to be able to update the files here with addition kits of parts as I have time to produce them. Additional to the common place frosting nozzles in the market today the abilities of 3D printing technology can really push the envelope on what's possible in nozzle design. Not being held to the limitations of sheet metal pressing and injection molding users can create a vast array of new shapes to really give that unique look they strive for. 3D printing also allows for less waste, users can print out only the parts they want and save money and maybe the environment.
I've included a zip folder with the SolidWorks (boo =( I'm sorry it's not open it's what I had access to) files so that users can add their own nozzle designs. Also included are zip files with STL files, and IGES Files.
Since I Don't have a Thing-O-Matic I am not 100% sure that these designs will print flawlessly which is why ive listed it as a work in progress. I did try to minimize extreme overhangs and wall thicknesses. I hope to get some feedback from the community as what needs to be improved to get these to print as well as possible. Thanks for taking a look and enjoy!

I suggest downloading at least the "Frosting Extruder Kit.STL", it comes with the primary components for the extruder as well as an assortment of tips to try out. To expand on the primary kit of parts you can download the following sets of nozzles: Round Nozzle Set.STL
Square Nozzle Set.STL
Slotted Nozzle Set.STL
Star Nozzle Set.STL
Hollow Nozzle Core Set.STL These should load into ReplicatorG in the correct orientation. If you would rather print individual parts download and open the "Primary Parts + Misc." folder and print the "Base" "Bag Bolt" and "Bag Puncture Tool." Then download and extract any of the "xxxxxx Nozzle - STL.zip" files and choose which nozzle you want to print, these individual files may need to be reoriented in ReplicatorG. USE:

  • Open a zip lock bag and put the threaded end of the "Bag Bolt" into one of the corners of the inside of the zip lock bag. Refer to the pictures at the left to see how this will all work.

  • Hold the bag bolt from the outside of the zip lock bag and screw the bag bolt + zip lock bag into the "base" hand tighten bag bolt, the angled faces of the bag bolt and base should meet and seal against the zip lock bag.

  • Take the "Bag Puncture Tool" and pass it through the bag bolt. this should pierce the zip lock bag. remove the bag puncture tool.

  • Choose your desired nozzle and screw it onto the base. If your using a hollow nozzle core with a round nozzle insert the core into the nozzle then screw the nozzle onto the base.

  • Fill the zip lock bag with your medium, seal and start extruding!

description.text:
To be mounted on front of extruder carriage of a Geeetech Prusa I3X.
It is a remix of a fan holder and my dial indicator holder.
I had to modify the nozzle to fit the fan. Depends on manufacturer of the fan I think.
This nozzle now will fit fans with 17,6 * 12,8 mm outlet.

Ok, after some printing problems reported and misaligning, I did some small redesigning.
Now the nozzle is a bit shorter, blows a bit downwards and points better to the extruder nozzle. On one side the nozzle is straight, thus easier to print without support.
The fan holder is also adjusted, shifted a few mm's to the right.. Making it better and better.. :-)

Printer:

Geeetech Prusa I3X

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

doesn't matter

Notes: No support is needed.
No bridge supporting, it will be a hell of a job to remove it afterwards. One funny thing: you could need a cooling fan with nozzle for those bridges.. :-D
Remove the thin support on top side of the nozzle, this is only ment for easier printing.

comments.text: For anyone else who's wondering how to deal with the GT2560 and a 2 pin PWM Signal. Simply find the PWM Fan out from the board, (The vertical facing port) And attach the red wire to the PWM Signal (Pin 1) and the Black wire to the common (Pin 2). This will allow you to control a 2 pin fan with variable speed and Gcodes.

description.text: A box for electronics

These are two simple designs for zipper handles.  The idea is that when you have gloves on or lack the dexterity to operate a zipper because of disability or other medical condition you would easily be able to open and close your coats, backpacks, camera bags, etc.  One is simply larger with an indentation while the other can be operated by sticking a finger through the hole.  You will need to use a bit or cord, shoelace, or ribbon to tie the ZipPads to your current zipper handle, or take off the current handle with some help and run the cord through the zipper itself.

In the photograph you see a very early test on my university's old cupcake machine.  The current designs are larger.  I post it so you see how the cord can be used to connect the end to the zipper handle.
